I lead Customer Marketing at Posit, and I'm so excited to have you joining us here today.

00:00:22.200 --> 00:00:27.559
If it's your first time ever joining us, the Hangout is our open space to hear what's going

00:00:27.559 --> 00:00:33.080
on in the world of data across all different industries, companies, get to chat about data

00:00:33.080 --> 00:00:39.000
science leadership, and connect with many others who are facing similar things as you.

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:43.840
And so we do get together here every Thursday at the same time, same place.

00:00:43.840 --> 00:00:49.639
So if you're watching this as a recording at some point in the future on YouTube, and

00:00:49.639 --> 00:00:54.639
you want to join us live, there's details to add it to your calendar below.

00:00:54.639 --> 00:00:59.400
Just make sure that it adds it for 12 Eastern Time and just double check the time zones.

00:00:59.400 --> 00:01:04.879
I know some people lately have had a few issues with the time zone, especially with Daylight

00:01:04.879 --> 00:01:08.239
Savings Time too.

00:01:08.239 --> 00:01:12.199
But if it is your first time joining us today, I'd love to have you say hi in the chat so

00:01:12.199 --> 00:01:18.519
that we can all welcome you in here and say hello and introduce ourselves too.

00:01:18.519 --> 00:01:23.599
We're all dedicated to keeping this a friendly and welcoming space for everybody.

00:01:23.599 --> 00:01:29.440
And so we love to hear from you, no matter of your years of experience, your titles,

00:01:29.440 --> 00:01:34.000
industry, or even languages that you work in.

00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:38.599
So if you're joining here, it's okay to just listen in if you want.

00:01:38.599 --> 00:01:43.000
Maybe you're on your lunch break, you're out walking your dogs or something, but also awesome

00:01:43.000 --> 00:01:46.239
to be a part of the party that happens in the Zoom chat.

00:01:46.239 --> 00:01:53.080
So you'll see there's a lot of conversation that happens there, links and resources shared,

00:01:53.080 --> 00:01:55.599
and just fun to meet people through the Zoom chat too.

00:01:55.599 --> 00:02:01.760
I know some people who end up being friends from meeting in the Hangout Zoom chat.

00:02:01.760 --> 00:02:06.720
But if you want to ask questions today and jump in, you can do so three different ways.

00:02:06.720 --> 00:02:13.479
So you can raise your hand on Zoom and I will call on you to jump in.

00:02:13.479 --> 00:02:18.240
You could put questions in the Zoom chat and just put a little star next to it if it's

00:02:18.240 --> 00:02:22.360
something that you want me to read out loud instead.

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:27.639
And then third, we have a Slido link where you can ask questions anonymously.

00:02:27.639 --> 00:02:31.240
And I am sure Curtis will go and grab that and put that there.

00:02:31.240 --> 00:02:32.720
Thank you.

00:02:32.720 --> 00:02:37.960
We do also have a LinkedIn group for the Hangouts, which can make it easier to find some people

00:02:37.960 --> 00:02:41.399
after the fact if you want to connect with each other.

00:02:41.399 --> 00:02:45.559
I'll just share that there as well.

00:02:45.559 --> 00:02:51.080
But as always, I like to add, no rule that you have to stay on the whole time or talk.

00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:53.320
You can come and go as it fits your schedule.

00:02:53.320 --> 00:02:56.839
Just happy to have you spending the time with us.

00:02:56.839 --> 00:03:02.199
But with that, I am so happy to be joined by my co-host today, Michael Durstine, Vice

00:03:02.199 --> 00:03:04.839
President at Wells Fargo.

00:03:04.839 --> 00:03:09.240
And Michael, to get us started here, I'd love to have you introduce yourself and share a

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:14.440
bit about your role today, but also something you like to do outside of work for fun.

00:03:14.440 --> 00:03:15.960
Oh, okay.

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:16.960
Yeah.

00:03:16.960 --> 00:03:19.479
Well, thanks for having me.

00:03:19.880 --> 00:03:20.360
Let's see.

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:23.000
I'll start with things that I like to do outside of work.

00:03:23.960 --> 00:03:26.039
I used to be a decent soccer player.

00:03:26.039 --> 00:03:28.919
I'm not very good anymore, but I still like to play.

00:03:29.880 --> 00:03:36.119
So I'll play futsal on like Monday nights, pretty, you know, whenever I can get away.

00:03:36.119 --> 00:03:36.619
Nice.

00:03:38.600 --> 00:03:39.399
Let's see.

00:03:39.399 --> 00:03:40.199
Yeah.

00:03:40.199 --> 00:03:43.320
A little bit about me or my background professionally.

00:03:43.320 --> 00:03:46.919
I am nearing my 10th year at Wells Fargo.

00:03:47.639 --> 00:03:54.440
And that time has been spent not necessarily doing the same thing, but working in the same

00:03:54.440 --> 00:04:00.440
kind of space, which is in mortgage, in mortgage finance.

00:04:02.199 --> 00:04:11.960
So what, you know, I started close to 10 years ago as a junior analyst doing a role that

00:04:11.960 --> 00:04:13.960
I think many people are familiar with.

00:04:16.279 --> 00:04:24.920
Pulling together, I mean, dozens of spreadsheets with hundreds of tabs, all other people's

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:30.920
models and work that's been recycled over years and years and years and just mazes of

00:04:30.920 --> 00:04:39.000
logic and making sure that nothing was wrong every morning before the traders on the trade

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:44.600
desk came in and started, you know, acting on these models, trading on these models.

00:04:45.160 --> 00:04:51.320
So there's a lot of stress to have before 6am every morning.

00:04:52.119 --> 00:05:00.679
So anyway, I was motivated to make my life easier and to make processes better.

00:05:01.239 --> 00:05:10.279
And so, you know, I think I grasped at everything I could to do that, which early on, the only

00:05:10.279 --> 00:05:16.679
corporate approved tools that I had were Excel, VBA, PowerShell.

00:05:16.679 --> 00:05:24.359
I did a lot of work in PowerShell, which, man, after, you know, using R and Python today,

00:05:24.359 --> 00:05:31.000
I just, I think about some of the things I had to do to get tables to work well and

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:32.200
things like that anyway.

00:05:33.720 --> 00:05:34.119
Yeah.

00:05:34.119 --> 00:05:36.839
And so that's really how I started.

00:05:36.839 --> 00:05:43.000
I just, I fell in love with building processes and making tools for other people that work

00:05:43.000 --> 00:05:43.559
really well.

00:05:44.279 --> 00:05:52.920
I think a few years into my career, I went to, I chose to go to graduate school, studied

00:05:52.920 --> 00:05:59.079
applied mathematics, specifically like quantitative finance at the University of Washington in

00:05:59.079 --> 00:05:59.640
Seattle.

00:05:59.640 --> 00:06:05.959
I did that program totally online over three years while I was working.

00:06:06.600 --> 00:06:15.480
And there I was introduced to R and C++ and just immediately, you know, as someone who's

00:06:15.480 --> 00:06:21.000
trying to do table manipulation with PowerShell, when you're introduced to R, it's like, oh

00:06:21.000 --> 00:06:24.920
my Lord, this is, everybody's thought of this already.

00:06:24.920 --> 00:06:31.399
All the tools are already here, has this amazing open source community of tool builders.

00:06:32.839 --> 00:06:33.799
It was wonderful.

00:06:33.799 --> 00:06:37.640
I immediately was just captured by it.

00:06:38.359 --> 00:06:40.600
So I think, when was that?

00:06:40.600 --> 00:06:50.279
That was probably in 2017 when I started using R and yeah, haven't looked back since.

00:06:51.399 --> 00:06:54.679
It really was a major turning point.

00:06:54.679 --> 00:06:58.519
It's transformative for me, for my career.

00:06:59.320 --> 00:07:06.119
It allowed me to kind of take on roles that other, I would just say, typical financial

00:07:06.119 --> 00:07:10.119
analysts in my field, my peers, they didn't have those skills.

00:07:10.920 --> 00:07:16.600
So I was brought into meetings that I probably didn't belong in, but because I could build

00:07:16.600 --> 00:07:19.239
things that other people couldn't build as easily.

00:07:21.399 --> 00:07:26.200
So yeah, I started working more with kind of our quantitative modelers who are building

00:07:26.839 --> 00:07:37.160
statistical and other, you know, kind of models to anticipate customer behavior in the mortgage

00:07:37.160 --> 00:07:37.559
space.

00:07:38.440 --> 00:07:43.720
I also fell into a lot of data engineering and data scientist roles, which can be really

00:07:43.720 --> 00:07:44.040
fun.

00:07:44.440 --> 00:07:55.959
And yeah, I think all of that over time just aggregated into me becoming more of a, yeah,

00:07:55.959 --> 00:07:57.880
I guess, official titles vice president.

00:07:57.880 --> 00:08:05.160
But really what that means is I just manage a team of analysts, of high ranking analysts.

00:08:05.160 --> 00:08:10.200
And so now my job isn't as fun.

00:08:10.200 --> 00:08:13.640
I don't get to code near as much as I want to.

00:08:13.640 --> 00:08:20.519
In fact, a lot of times I'll find myself coding in my free time because I don't get

00:08:20.519 --> 00:08:21.559
to do it at work anymore.

00:08:22.200 --> 00:08:27.000
So that's a personal problem that I'm trying to figure out and work through.

00:08:28.359 --> 00:08:36.919
But instead, I have a team of analysts that are excited now to kind of learn new things,

00:08:36.919 --> 00:08:38.119
solve problems.

00:08:38.119 --> 00:08:46.840
And so it's new for me to be in a coaching role and to work on problems with people,

00:08:46.840 --> 00:08:51.799
to try to, yeah, untangle a knot or put together a puzzle.

00:08:54.200 --> 00:08:55.159
It is fun.

00:08:55.159 --> 00:08:56.840
It's fun in a different way.

00:08:57.799 --> 00:08:59.320
So yeah, that's my role today.

00:08:59.320 --> 00:09:05.880
And then when I'm not actively working on problems, I am usually on calls advocating

00:09:05.880 --> 00:09:12.200
for analysts, advocating for projects or ways to build things and trying to convince

00:09:13.000 --> 00:09:21.000
the directors and the executives above me to make more or to make certain strategic

00:09:21.000 --> 00:09:22.760
and tactical decisions.

00:09:22.760 --> 00:09:25.000
Anyway, I know that was long winded, but thank you.

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:26.520
No, that was that was great.

00:09:26.520 --> 00:09:27.080
Thank you.

00:09:27.080 --> 00:09:33.080
I love when you were telling me that story about like you having to go in to work at

00:09:33.080 --> 00:09:38.359
5 a.m. and like pull together these spreadsheets because I could just like picture that and

00:09:38.359 --> 00:09:40.520
thinking like there must be a better way.

00:09:40.520 --> 00:09:46.119
But what was your like final breaking point with that, like where you turn to data science?

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:56.599
So I think honestly, when I moved past that role, really, that was really an intro role

00:09:56.599 --> 00:10:02.599
in my group to kind of put new analysts to the gauntlet a little bit.

00:10:03.479 --> 00:10:04.919
So I moved past that role.

00:10:05.559 --> 00:10:10.679
And after a few years, I gained some of these skills in R and Python and whatnot.

00:10:12.039 --> 00:10:15.000
I kind of looked back and I'm like, we should not have that.

00:10:15.000 --> 00:10:17.799
That should not I don't care if it's a rite of passage.

00:10:18.840 --> 00:10:25.479
That's a mess and it's operational risk because I was really tired and I could have easily

00:10:25.479 --> 00:10:30.039
broken something that would have cost the bank some, you know, financially.

00:10:30.039 --> 00:10:35.880
If a trader trades on bad decisions and they have to unwind that, you're opening up the

00:10:35.880 --> 00:10:36.760
company to a loss.

00:10:37.400 --> 00:10:44.840
So it was not popular because often it's don't fix something that's not broken.

00:10:45.960 --> 00:10:47.960
That was the mentality.

00:10:47.960 --> 00:10:54.599
And so slowly, I've worked to build challenger processes.

00:10:54.599 --> 00:11:01.479
I mean, I feel like the only way to get something done in my company is you have to build something

00:11:01.479 --> 00:11:02.200
in parallel.

00:11:03.719 --> 00:11:05.960
It operates on its own.

00:11:05.960 --> 00:11:07.479
It's a competing product.

00:11:08.200 --> 00:11:14.359
And then you have to run it side by side and absolutely obliterate the old competition.

00:11:14.359 --> 00:11:16.280
You have to show why this is so much better.

00:11:17.960 --> 00:11:19.880
Tell the story to your bosses.

00:11:20.440 --> 00:11:21.640
And so we were able to do that.

00:11:22.599 --> 00:11:30.440
The program that runs today that does what I used to do 10 years ago runs completely

00:11:30.440 --> 00:11:34.840
in R. It runs on a server, on a Linux box every night.

00:11:35.559 --> 00:11:37.799
And it's completely automated.

00:11:37.799 --> 00:11:39.799
There's no junior analyst that has to do it.

00:11:41.080 --> 00:11:45.559
Nobody has to wake up at 5 a.m. or really at 4.30, get at the office at 5.

00:11:47.640 --> 00:11:48.140
Yeah.

00:11:49.159 --> 00:11:51.320
I mean, those junior analyst roles still exist.

00:11:52.039 --> 00:11:58.119
But now we're encouraging them to learn R or to try new things or to do data science,

00:11:58.119 --> 00:11:58.440
right?

00:11:58.440 --> 00:12:03.080
They're not just filling out spreadsheets or making sure that this is green and this

00:12:03.080 --> 00:12:03.640
is red.

00:12:03.640 --> 00:12:06.679
And it's just a different role now.

00:12:06.679 --> 00:12:07.239
And so, yeah.

00:12:09.479 --> 00:12:14.679
Honestly, the R program, just to give a little bit more detail, it sits on that server and

00:12:14.679 --> 00:12:18.679
it waits for upstream models and other calculations to be finished.

00:12:18.679 --> 00:12:20.359
So it's just a waiting.

00:12:21.960 --> 00:12:30.760
And it aggregates that information, calculates downstream things and pushes those results

00:12:30.760 --> 00:12:34.919
into a cloud database, basically.

00:12:35.799 --> 00:12:38.359
Then all of our visualizations and reports are built on.

00:12:38.359 --> 00:12:39.479
So I'm very proud of that.

00:12:39.479 --> 00:12:47.159
But it was a lot of work technically and maybe even more work politically to get that through.

00:12:48.760 --> 00:12:50.280
Such an awesome example.

00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:50.760
Thank you.

00:12:51.559 --> 00:12:52.059
Yeah.

00:12:52.599 --> 00:12:55.080
Liz, I see you had asked a question in the chat.

00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:56.119
Do you want to jump in here?

00:12:58.599 --> 00:12:59.099
Sure.

00:13:00.599 --> 00:13:02.039
Thank you for sharing all of that.

00:13:03.239 --> 00:13:06.039
I think we can all kind of identify with that to a certain extent.

00:13:07.960 --> 00:13:13.479
And in my role as a data analyst, we also had to push really hard to get our stuff on

00:13:13.479 --> 00:13:13.880
a cloud.

00:13:15.719 --> 00:13:18.359
But my question is a multi-part question.

00:13:18.359 --> 00:13:20.760
So feel free to ignore some of it if you want.

00:13:22.760 --> 00:13:27.400
So is your current toolbox limited to R and Python?

00:13:27.400 --> 00:13:33.239
And what are your feelings, if any, on VS Code and Git Copilot?

00:13:33.239 --> 00:13:40.200
And in your current role, how knowledgeable do you need to remain on the rapidly developing

00:13:40.200 --> 00:13:41.400
data science landscape?

00:13:42.440 --> 00:13:43.799
Yeah, that's a great question.

00:13:44.760 --> 00:13:56.359
So as far as my company specifically, we are trying to upskill, whatever that means,

00:13:57.960 --> 00:13:58.919
as much as possible.

00:13:58.919 --> 00:14:03.880
We have a lot of very talented financial analysts with business knowledge, and they're usually

00:14:03.880 --> 00:14:06.760
all great or think they're great with Excel.

00:14:08.280 --> 00:14:11.640
We're trying to teach Python across the company.

00:14:11.719 --> 00:14:13.640
I've been a voice.

00:14:13.640 --> 00:14:18.679
There's a few other people that say, really, this should be multilingual, right?

00:14:19.559 --> 00:14:21.479
R is a great tool.

00:14:21.479 --> 00:14:26.119
A lot of analysts find it more accessible to start or even long term.

00:14:26.119 --> 00:14:30.039
There's certain problems that I prefer R to solve problems.

00:14:30.039 --> 00:14:34.280
There's certain problems that Python could be better here, right?

00:14:35.880 --> 00:14:40.840
Or even people that just have really pure SQL skills.

00:14:40.919 --> 00:14:47.239
I mean, there's new technology now, like DuckDB, where you can really write pure SQL and connect

00:14:47.239 --> 00:14:48.919
it to Python, connect it to R.

00:14:48.919 --> 00:14:54.359
I mean, it's so exciting now how easy it is to connect processes together.

00:14:55.960 --> 00:14:59.559
So no, I don't think we're necessarily limited to just those boxes.

00:15:00.520 --> 00:15:05.479
But as a company, we are trying intentionally to limit the scope of what tools are we going

00:15:05.479 --> 00:15:10.440
to use to solve problems because we have to manage it somehow, right?

00:15:10.440 --> 00:15:17.320
I think also from my boss's several layers up perspective, they don't really understand

00:15:18.760 --> 00:15:21.719
how effective good change management can be.

00:15:22.520 --> 00:15:30.919
So Git and GitHub, and if you really are using these tools effectively, you can control source.

00:15:33.320 --> 00:15:38.520
So yeah, I think, let me backtrack and make sure I'm answering your questions.

00:15:38.760 --> 00:15:48.280
Yeah, I do think we're trying to be multifaceted in what we're using, try to use the best tool

00:15:48.280 --> 00:15:48.840
for the job.

00:15:49.799 --> 00:15:51.799
VS Code, I love VS Code.

00:15:52.599 --> 00:15:54.840
I use it for Python.

00:15:54.840 --> 00:15:59.400
I use it for R sometimes, especially if I have a project that requires both.

00:16:00.039 --> 00:16:08.679
Even though, I mean, I see that RStudio, you can run Python pretty effectively using Reticulate.

00:16:10.119 --> 00:16:11.799
Yeah, that's pretty slick too.

00:16:11.799 --> 00:16:19.239
I think most of the analysts on my team will use VS Code for Python or PyCharm for Python.

00:16:21.000 --> 00:16:24.200
We are not allowed to use Copilot yet as a company.

00:16:24.440 --> 00:16:29.799
That's just policy until somebody says it's allowed.

00:16:32.359 --> 00:16:33.400
Great, thank you.

00:16:33.400 --> 00:16:33.900
Yeah.

00:16:36.200 --> 00:16:38.280
Javier, I see you had a question in the chat.

00:16:38.280 --> 00:16:39.799
Want to jump in here next?

00:16:43.640 --> 00:16:44.440
Yeah, thanks, Rachel.

00:16:45.479 --> 00:16:47.719
Michael, I've loved your comments so far.

00:16:47.719 --> 00:16:50.440
Your background sounds awesome, as does the work you do.

00:16:50.520 --> 00:16:53.159
I'm no longer in finance, but I started my career in finance.

00:16:54.359 --> 00:16:58.359
And I was doing more like M&A and valuation type work.

00:16:58.359 --> 00:17:05.400
So maybe less aligned with the quant finance work per se, or like, you know, financing.

00:17:05.400 --> 00:17:07.400
Like, that's definitely not something I was doing.

00:17:07.400 --> 00:17:11.479
But anyway, I still keep up with some of the chatter.

00:17:11.479 --> 00:17:16.280
And over the years, I've seen a trend of like, you know, more finance professionals talking

00:17:16.520 --> 00:17:22.040
about data science, whether it's like use cases with R or Python or whatever it might be.

00:17:22.040 --> 00:17:28.839
And just today, I was seeing this long kind of discussion thread on LinkedIn about how

00:17:29.719 --> 00:17:37.880
quant finance managers and banking finance managers have had a hard time hiring data

00:17:37.880 --> 00:17:44.359
scientists and putting them into, you know, the capacity to do the work that they do.

00:17:44.599 --> 00:17:49.160
You know, the capacity of like a quant, for lack of better words.

00:17:49.160 --> 00:17:51.479
I'm using that term pretty loosely here.

00:17:51.479 --> 00:17:54.599
But yeah, I mean, it was a bit surprising to me.

00:17:54.599 --> 00:17:56.280
And, you know, I'm out of that world now.

00:17:56.280 --> 00:18:00.280
But I'm just curious if that's like a sentiment you share or, you know,

00:18:00.280 --> 00:18:02.599
what maybe your perspectives are around that.

00:18:02.599 --> 00:18:08.520
Like, do you feel like some of the data scientists that might excel at R or excel at Python

00:18:08.520 --> 00:18:14.040
actually lack like the math chops to really succeed in those roles?

00:18:14.839 --> 00:18:15.479
I don't know.

00:18:15.479 --> 00:18:15.800
Yeah.

00:18:15.800 --> 00:18:17.319
Open-ended question here.

00:18:17.319 --> 00:18:19.800
No, no, I think that's a great question.

00:18:19.800 --> 00:18:22.680
And I think the short answer is yes, it's been challenging.

00:18:22.680 --> 00:18:25.319
But maybe the reason why might be unique.

00:18:27.239 --> 00:18:35.160
So again, I work at Wells Fargo, which I don't think it's any secret that the last seven years

00:18:35.239 --> 00:18:41.239
have been difficult for this company because of sales practices that were happening on

00:18:41.239 --> 00:18:50.119
the retail side of things, where basically we were opening false credit card accounts

00:18:50.119 --> 00:18:55.000
for individuals to basically increase sales metrics.

00:18:55.000 --> 00:19:00.199
So the Federal Reserve and the federal government put an asset cap on this company

00:19:00.920 --> 00:19:06.680
and forced us to really clean up our governance and things like that.

00:19:07.800 --> 00:19:13.560
So having said that, it's been difficult to hire anybody for seven years.

00:19:16.040 --> 00:19:19.880
So yeah, I'll start with that.

00:19:20.199 --> 00:19:27.880
But secondly, I do think there is some middle space that is needed between

00:19:29.800 --> 00:19:36.199
or really where we had a roster of financial analysts before that were really savvy and

00:19:36.199 --> 00:19:41.640
good with cash flow models, discounting valuation models, things like that.

00:19:42.439 --> 00:19:49.880
We're trying to build an in-house team here with R and Python skills.

00:19:49.880 --> 00:19:54.439
We want them to be doing that same kind of work, that same kind of analysis, but with

00:19:54.439 --> 00:19:55.400
a new tool set.

00:19:57.160 --> 00:20:06.760
So that's really the role that I'm in today, is I have a roster of analysts that are pretty

00:20:06.760 --> 00:20:11.640
technically savvy, but we're supposed to be going outbound and teaching others.

00:20:11.640 --> 00:20:14.839
Teaching is a core part of what our team does.

00:20:16.439 --> 00:20:19.400
But hiring has been tough, just as a company.

00:20:19.400 --> 00:20:24.839
I'm not sure exactly how other banks are handling that middle ground right now, where

00:20:24.839 --> 00:20:27.880
you want upskilling, like I said.

00:20:29.479 --> 00:20:32.119
I don't know if that was a sharp answer or not, but...

00:20:32.119 --> 00:20:33.719
No, no, no, that's good.

00:20:33.719 --> 00:20:36.040
Yeah, it was an open-ended question anyway.

00:20:36.040 --> 00:20:38.119
And then just a quick follow-up.

00:20:38.119 --> 00:20:46.439
Do you see in banking that there's a space for, let's say, individual contributors to

00:20:46.439 --> 00:20:51.400
keep moving up in their careers, or do you feel like it's more of you kind of need to

00:20:51.400 --> 00:20:54.839
go into management or you're out?

00:20:54.839 --> 00:20:55.959
I hope so.

00:20:55.959 --> 00:20:56.599
I hope so.

00:20:58.520 --> 00:21:02.280
At Wells, I know we have a program that we're trying to do that.

00:21:02.280 --> 00:21:10.040
We're trying to really incentivize rockstar sole contributors to stay doing what they

00:21:10.040 --> 00:21:11.000
do great, right?

00:21:11.000 --> 00:21:13.880
Building processes, building tools.

00:21:16.119 --> 00:21:27.000
Yeah, I think management, so far, it has its ups and downs to speaking cliches.

00:21:27.400 --> 00:21:30.760
But also, I think part of my job isn't just managing.

00:21:30.760 --> 00:21:33.319
It's not just being a manager and not doing the work.

00:21:34.199 --> 00:21:43.479
I think part of the reason why I'm kind of put in this position is because I work hard

00:21:43.479 --> 00:21:44.839
to influence people.

00:21:45.400 --> 00:21:54.520
I really, I try to partner with other teams that aren't, you know, on an org chart, direct,

00:21:54.680 --> 00:21:55.959
you know, directly under me.

00:21:55.959 --> 00:21:59.000
They have no reason to help me, right?

00:21:59.000 --> 00:22:04.439
Besides the fact that I've helped them in the past, or that we've worked on projects

00:22:04.439 --> 00:22:08.680
in the past and we think alike, and we like working together.

00:22:09.400 --> 00:22:11.079
We like solving problems together.

00:22:11.640 --> 00:22:20.520
So, you know, whether that's a formal manager or not, or a sole contributor, I think really

00:22:20.920 --> 00:22:25.880
what's most important to organizations is having people that are facilitators, that

00:22:25.880 --> 00:22:27.959
are connectors, right?

00:22:28.839 --> 00:22:37.479
Because at a certain point in the bank, or probably at any big company, technical skill

00:22:37.479 --> 00:22:40.040
doesn't scale anymore, right?

00:22:40.040 --> 00:22:46.599
Like I'm at a point right now where I have 30 or 40 hard problems that I'm being asked

00:22:46.599 --> 00:22:47.160
to solve.

00:22:47.160 --> 00:22:49.400
And I, they're all interesting.

00:22:49.400 --> 00:22:51.719
They're all, well, a lot of them are interesting.

00:22:51.719 --> 00:22:57.079
They're not all interesting, but I wish I could spend a couple of days each chewing

00:22:57.079 --> 00:23:00.359
on each problem and finding out a way to solve it.

00:23:00.359 --> 00:23:03.000
I can't, I can't, I don't have enough time.

00:23:04.599 --> 00:23:11.880
So one, I have to coach people that are also very talented and curious on how to solve

00:23:11.880 --> 00:23:12.439
these problems.

00:23:12.439 --> 00:23:17.560
And not every solution is how I'd want to do it, but that, you know, there's a, there's

00:23:17.560 --> 00:23:21.479
a cost benefit analysis that you have to perform there.

00:23:22.119 --> 00:23:27.079
And for jobs that my team can't do, yeah, I have to go outbound.

00:23:27.079 --> 00:23:29.719
I have to figure out who can do this in the company.

00:23:29.719 --> 00:23:37.880
So, yeah, I know that it's maybe a, a case for the management route and maybe that, maybe

00:23:37.880 --> 00:23:40.520
I'm just, I'm just, I don't know.

00:23:40.599 --> 00:23:48.119
Maybe I'm just explaining why I sold my soul, but yeah, that's, that's kind of how I see

00:23:48.119 --> 00:23:48.280
it.

00:23:49.640 --> 00:23:55.880
I love this, the focus on relationships here and that like facilitation role as well.

00:23:56.520 --> 00:24:00.599
I think, Adam, this actually might, this is a great time, I think, for your question you

00:24:00.599 --> 00:24:01.560
asked a bit earlier.

00:24:01.560 --> 00:24:02.760
Do you want to jump in here?

00:24:02.760 --> 00:24:04.040
Yeah, that was the perfect tie-in.

00:24:04.040 --> 00:24:04.439
Thank you.

00:24:05.079 --> 00:24:10.280
Because I'm constantly thinking about that political piece, the relationships, how we

00:24:10.280 --> 00:24:15.000
work with business partners and like what the role of data science really is with respect

00:24:15.000 --> 00:24:19.560
to the business where, you know, our goal is at the end of the day to like, to sell

00:24:19.560 --> 00:24:19.880
stuff.

00:24:19.880 --> 00:24:24.359
And I see data science as like one tool that fits into this big, broad picture.

00:24:24.359 --> 00:24:28.199
But I'm wondering about like, I mean, you mentioned the bridge building and the

00:24:28.199 --> 00:24:29.000
connections.

00:24:29.000 --> 00:24:33.640
Do you have, besides that, do you have a framework for building those relationships and

00:24:33.640 --> 00:24:34.439
getting buy-in?

00:24:34.439 --> 00:24:40.199
Do you have like quantitative frameworks for showing value of an initiative before it's

00:24:40.199 --> 00:24:40.680
implemented?

00:24:40.680 --> 00:24:42.199
Like how you think about that kind of stuff?

00:24:43.160 --> 00:24:47.719
No, I think short answer is I could be, I could be better at that.

00:24:50.760 --> 00:24:53.079
So my boss is a storyteller.

00:24:53.079 --> 00:24:56.439
He loves, he is, he's great with people.

00:24:58.040 --> 00:25:02.040
He can go on and he's a little flamboyant.

00:25:04.280 --> 00:25:07.000
And so he likes to think in stories.

00:25:08.599 --> 00:25:13.880
As far as really technical data science, like he's just, it doesn't, it doesn't

00:25:13.880 --> 00:25:14.760
register with him.

00:25:17.880 --> 00:25:23.479
So I think in my personal world, I've been working for the same guy for a while too.

00:25:23.479 --> 00:25:27.719
So a lot of my work has to also flow that way.

00:25:27.719 --> 00:25:30.439
I will, I will interpret the metrics.

00:25:30.439 --> 00:25:36.599
I will try to understand what, you know, direction tactically we need to go, what,

00:25:36.599 --> 00:25:40.040
where we need to focus energy, these, these kinds of things, or what, what we need to

00:25:40.040 --> 00:25:40.839
build.

00:25:40.839 --> 00:25:44.520
But then going up, I have to make that into a story.

00:25:45.319 --> 00:25:46.920
And usually it's verbal or written.

00:25:49.479 --> 00:25:51.239
His boss is the exact same way.

00:25:51.800 --> 00:26:02.119
So that's, that's kind of the, the really analytics part usually stops or stops around

00:26:02.119 --> 00:26:02.619
me.

00:26:03.959 --> 00:26:05.160
That's not the case for everyone.

00:26:05.160 --> 00:26:08.280
I know some executives that are very number driven.

00:26:08.839 --> 00:26:12.599
They need, they need to see the actual, and it's usually because they had a background

00:26:12.599 --> 00:26:13.160
like ours.

00:26:14.839 --> 00:26:16.040
So yeah.

00:26:17.560 --> 00:26:20.199
Short answer, not for my boss.

00:26:21.479 --> 00:26:21.800
Yeah.

00:26:21.800 --> 00:26:26.199
I mean, I can relate to that because I know a number of projects that I've worked on that

00:26:26.199 --> 00:26:27.319
have failed.

00:26:27.319 --> 00:26:30.280
It's often because I'm trying to get too quantitative.

00:26:30.280 --> 00:26:31.640
I'm trying to get too in the weeds.

00:26:31.640 --> 00:26:34.040
I'm not telling that, that narrative arc.

00:26:35.239 --> 00:26:36.359
So that's very interesting.

00:26:36.359 --> 00:26:40.439
I think it's so hard because when you build something that's fantastic, you fall in love

00:26:40.439 --> 00:26:41.319
with it, right?

00:26:41.319 --> 00:26:43.400
Like you, you know, this is great.

00:26:43.400 --> 00:26:44.439
This is fantastic.

00:26:44.439 --> 00:26:47.959
And you need to see how hard this was to solve.

00:26:47.959 --> 00:26:48.459
Right.

00:26:48.939 --> 00:26:56.540
And I just try to humble myself and remember how busy my bosses are and how many, like

00:26:56.540 --> 00:26:59.979
if I have 40 projects, they have 200 projects, right?

00:27:00.780 --> 00:27:04.540
So what, how do you capture their imagination?

00:27:04.540 --> 00:27:10.060
And unfortunately it's not how cool of a problem this was that you solve.

00:27:10.060 --> 00:27:12.699
It's what is this going to do for them?

00:27:12.699 --> 00:27:15.819
How is this going to make this place better?

00:27:15.819 --> 00:27:17.020
Their life easier.

00:27:17.979 --> 00:27:19.099
That kind of thing.

00:27:19.099 --> 00:27:25.660
And so, yeah, unfortunately I think it is like putting on your, you know, best Don Draper

00:27:25.660 --> 00:27:27.819
face and selling it, you know?

00:27:29.739 --> 00:27:30.619
I don't know.

00:27:30.619 --> 00:27:30.859
Yeah.

00:27:30.859 --> 00:27:31.500
No, well said.

00:27:31.500 --> 00:27:32.000
Thank you.

00:27:36.060 --> 00:27:36.560
Awesome.

00:27:37.979 --> 00:27:38.540
I love that.

00:27:38.540 --> 00:27:43.579
We've been talking a lot about Madman presentations internally, like having those big picture

00:27:44.140 --> 00:27:45.020
presentations.

00:27:45.020 --> 00:27:45.520
Sure.

00:27:47.420 --> 00:27:51.099
I'm going to jump over to Jesse's question.

00:27:51.819 --> 00:27:53.180
Oh, I see a star here.

00:27:53.180 --> 00:27:54.380
So I'll read it.

00:27:54.380 --> 00:27:57.979
And let me know if my wifi is getting a little spotty.

00:27:57.979 --> 00:27:58.540
Am I okay?

00:27:59.420 --> 00:28:00.219
So far so good.

00:28:00.219 --> 00:28:00.540
Okay.

00:28:00.540 --> 00:28:01.660
People got, okay.

00:28:01.660 --> 00:28:03.660
People got choppy for me for one second.

00:28:03.660 --> 00:28:09.260
But the question from Jesse was, what are some problems that you see R being more useful

00:28:09.260 --> 00:28:11.339
for tackling and vice versa?

00:28:11.339 --> 00:28:14.540
What are some problems that you see Python being more useful for?

00:28:15.180 --> 00:28:16.619
That's a great question.

00:28:16.619 --> 00:28:25.099
So personally, I find R to be my favorite language to program in because I don't know,

00:28:25.099 --> 00:28:32.699
it may be, I think specifically kind of the tidy verse dialects.

00:28:34.219 --> 00:28:41.339
When I have to work with tabular data and I really need to take multiple sources of

00:28:41.339 --> 00:28:47.819
data and, you know, transform into information.

00:28:48.619 --> 00:28:49.500
It's like gardening.

00:28:49.500 --> 00:28:56.300
I know other people have said that, but it really is something that I find to be kind

00:28:56.300 --> 00:28:56.939
of tranquil.

00:28:59.180 --> 00:29:06.540
So when I think of pure, yeah, data transformation, tabular data transformation, R is my go-to.

00:29:07.099 --> 00:29:14.060
And I think it will be, and I know Python has counterparts, like whether you use pandas

00:29:14.060 --> 00:29:16.219
or pollers, pollers is now popular.

00:29:17.500 --> 00:29:18.140
Great.

00:29:18.140 --> 00:29:18.780
Fantastic.

00:29:19.579 --> 00:29:23.500
I enjoy writing in R tidy verse more than I like writing pollers.

00:29:25.900 --> 00:29:33.500
So I think there's a wonderful thing about today is that preferences can be, you know,

00:29:33.500 --> 00:29:34.619
your preference is great.

00:29:35.420 --> 00:29:36.380
It's perfectly fine.

00:29:36.380 --> 00:29:37.260
We can work with it.

00:29:38.780 --> 00:29:46.060
As far as Python, what I have found Python to be really better for, or just personally,

00:29:46.060 --> 00:29:53.660
personal opinion is when I have to work, if I had to do something that's object oriented,

00:29:53.660 --> 00:30:00.780
I try, I usually use Python to create classes and things like that.

00:30:00.780 --> 00:30:03.020
I know R has some of that functionality as well.

00:30:03.739 --> 00:30:06.219
I just think Python is a little cleaner.

00:30:08.540 --> 00:30:18.060
Also, when I have to, so we orchestrate our processes using Daxter now.

00:30:18.780 --> 00:30:23.900
And so that's a Python based orchestration tool.

00:30:23.900 --> 00:30:27.739
And so we will package individual tasks, right?

00:30:28.540 --> 00:30:31.260
That have to happen, individual transformations.

00:30:31.260 --> 00:30:32.859
Those can be an R or Python.

00:30:32.859 --> 00:30:33.500
Doesn't matter.

00:30:34.219 --> 00:30:39.979
We'll either write to parquet and trans, you know, transfer between the two languages,

00:30:39.979 --> 00:30:43.500
or we will use DuckDB.

00:30:43.500 --> 00:30:49.099
For example, I brought it up earlier to kind of create a little mini database that works

00:30:49.099 --> 00:30:50.780
with both Python and R just fine.

00:30:51.420 --> 00:30:59.579
So that's kind of how we will, you know, transmit data from language to language in the same

00:30:59.579 --> 00:31:00.079
flow.

00:31:01.500 --> 00:31:02.000
Yeah.

00:31:03.500 --> 00:31:04.000
Thank you.

00:31:05.739 --> 00:31:10.219
Morgana, I see you had a question around AI.

00:31:10.219 --> 00:31:11.099
Do you want to jump in?

00:31:12.780 --> 00:31:13.420
Sure.

00:31:13.420 --> 00:31:14.140
Thanks, Rachel.

00:31:15.819 --> 00:31:19.180
So my question was around AI.

00:31:20.619 --> 00:31:23.099
I feel like it's all over the place right now.

00:31:23.819 --> 00:31:30.699
There's kind of a big push for everybody to spin up and become AI professionals as fast

00:31:30.699 --> 00:31:36.619
as we learn what AI is and as fast as the GPT models are being created.

00:31:37.260 --> 00:31:42.459
What are you doing in your office to kind of help your existing team scale up?

00:31:42.459 --> 00:31:44.859
Well, scale up and meet that demand.

00:31:45.420 --> 00:31:45.920
Yeah.

00:31:45.979 --> 00:31:53.819
So like, like I said earlier, I think we are slow to the party because as a company, we're

00:31:53.819 --> 00:31:57.020
not allowing analysts to use AI assistance yet.

00:31:59.739 --> 00:32:01.579
I don't think that's far away.

00:32:02.540 --> 00:32:09.819
Because just in personal usage, I find it to be incredibly helpful.

00:32:09.900 --> 00:32:18.380
I find the answers that I get out of LLM models to often be wrong or imprecise, but often

00:32:18.380 --> 00:32:19.420
helpful, right?

00:32:19.420 --> 00:32:20.699
It gets me closer.

00:32:20.699 --> 00:32:21.739
And then I can iterate.

00:32:21.739 --> 00:32:24.140
Okay, no, that's not the right question to ask.

00:32:24.699 --> 00:32:29.339
Usually by the time I get to the right question, I understand what the answer is.

00:32:29.339 --> 00:32:31.099
It's funny how that works, right?

00:32:31.099 --> 00:32:33.579
Where you're like, oh, my question was wrong.

00:32:34.300 --> 00:32:36.540
And so you're kind of iterating on that.

00:32:36.540 --> 00:32:45.979
So I do think that for senior or even for skilled analysts, that's going to be an incredibly

00:32:45.979 --> 00:32:49.500
valuable tool that's going to accelerate development time.

00:32:50.380 --> 00:32:57.579
You know, maybe not some of these people are like 60, 70, no, but maybe 30%, 20% faster

00:32:57.579 --> 00:32:59.579
to solve problems.

00:32:59.819 --> 00:33:03.579
I just don't understand how anybody can leave that on off the table.

00:33:05.660 --> 00:33:09.260
But yeah, now for a junior analyst, right?

00:33:09.260 --> 00:33:14.540
Like when I was starting to rewind 10 years ago, I don't know if I would have known what

00:33:14.540 --> 00:33:15.579
to do with it.

00:33:15.579 --> 00:33:19.260
You know, like, I just I wouldn't know at all what questions to ask.

00:33:20.300 --> 00:33:28.060
So in my head, I haven't mapped out how people growing alongside of me, you know, how I'm

00:33:28.060 --> 00:33:33.180
people growing alongside these models, how that exactly is going to play out yet.

00:33:35.420 --> 00:33:35.920
Yeah.

00:33:36.780 --> 00:33:37.280
Thank you.

00:33:38.380 --> 00:33:40.780
Yeah, and I feel like that makes a lot of sense.

00:33:40.780 --> 00:33:41.500
So thank you.

00:33:41.500 --> 00:33:46.780
We're kind of in a little bit of a similar boat in my office where some tools are allowed,

00:33:46.780 --> 00:33:47.660
some aren't.

00:33:47.660 --> 00:33:53.500
But at the same time, there's sort of a need to have people understand all of the principles

00:33:53.500 --> 00:33:55.819
behind the tools that we can't use yet.

00:33:56.780 --> 00:34:01.819
So it's sort of an interesting, interesting way to way that we're learning.

00:34:01.819 --> 00:34:03.339
And thank you for your time.

00:34:04.380 --> 00:34:05.420
Yeah, absolutely.

00:34:05.420 --> 00:34:08.939
That's going to be one of the trickiest part about parts about this, right?

00:34:08.939 --> 00:34:12.300
It's policy, policy around these models.

00:34:13.899 --> 00:34:17.260
Totally undefined yet in my company, I'm sure.

00:34:20.300 --> 00:34:22.300
I see Bill had a question.

00:34:22.300 --> 00:34:24.139
There's a star next to it, so I'll read it.

00:34:24.699 --> 00:34:27.020
But it was in partnering with other teams.

00:34:27.020 --> 00:34:31.020
Are you on site where you can meet at a water cooler or coffee machine?

00:34:31.020 --> 00:34:34.939
How do you network internally in the age of remote work?

00:34:35.739 --> 00:34:36.540
Very difficult.

00:34:37.899 --> 00:34:42.219
And people don't agree on what's happening here.

00:34:42.219 --> 00:34:44.459
So we come into the office three days a week.

00:34:45.820 --> 00:34:49.580
I'm in St. Louis, and I live 25 minutes from the office.

00:34:49.580 --> 00:34:58.219
And St. Louis is a pretty easy trip for me.

00:35:00.620 --> 00:35:02.860
However, I work with people that are in Charlotte,

00:35:02.860 --> 00:35:04.379
work with people that are in New York City.

00:35:05.340 --> 00:35:11.979
So I have a little bit of both where I can, yeah, meet with people in person,

00:35:11.979 --> 00:35:18.620
really rely on that person to person communication to get things done.

00:35:18.620 --> 00:35:21.580
But I also have partners that are totally remote.

00:35:23.580 --> 00:35:28.780
That is, I don't think there's a perfect solution to communication today.

00:35:29.580 --> 00:35:36.060
We learned that during COVID where we had to quickly learn how to do everything a different way.

00:35:36.060 --> 00:35:41.580
And now the problem is almost harder because it's not one way or the other, it's both.

00:35:41.580 --> 00:35:42.620
Everybody's trying to do both.

00:35:43.580 --> 00:35:49.659
And I think that just makes middle manager's job way harder.

00:35:50.219 --> 00:35:52.860
How do you communicate with people in the best

00:35:54.939 --> 00:35:59.580
way possible for the specific task you're trying to do?

00:36:01.100 --> 00:36:04.379
So what I'm trying to do with my team is,

00:36:04.379 --> 00:36:07.820
yeah, it really depends on what the purpose of the communication is.

00:36:08.219 --> 00:36:13.580
If we have to solve a problem and it's challenging,

00:36:15.979 --> 00:36:18.699
I would prefer to be in person with an actual whiteboard.

00:36:18.699 --> 00:36:19.820
I really would.

00:36:19.820 --> 00:36:23.179
We're going to lock ourselves into a room, we're going to try to solve it.

00:36:23.179 --> 00:36:27.820
If you can't be there in person, yeah, we're going to do everything we can

00:36:27.820 --> 00:36:30.540
to get you there virtually as well.

00:36:30.540 --> 00:36:35.580
We'll get you hooked up with a shared screen, shared whiteboard,

00:36:36.379 --> 00:36:37.260
things like that.

00:36:37.260 --> 00:36:42.780
I mean, I'm lucky that at this company, we have those resources that we can use those.

00:36:42.780 --> 00:36:46.699
But I think they're pretty readily available in most places.

00:36:47.419 --> 00:36:53.260
So yeah, I just, I think the interaction has become harder.

00:36:55.659 --> 00:37:01.260
And I just, it's going to take time to solve it and you have to be more thoughtful about it.

00:37:06.540 --> 00:37:10.540
Thinking about your past 10 years at the company,

00:37:10.540 --> 00:37:15.020
so going from junior analyst to your role now as the vice president,

00:37:15.580 --> 00:37:21.820
were there any valuable lessons you learned along the way in progressing through the company?

00:37:22.780 --> 00:37:26.699
I know we touched on the relationships piece, but any others that come to mind?

00:37:27.739 --> 00:37:32.860
Yeah, I think probably one of the larger things is patience,

00:37:33.659 --> 00:37:39.820
is understanding that when you work at a company of this size, things take time.

00:37:40.379 --> 00:37:43.179
Momentum has to be built over time.

00:37:43.179 --> 00:37:46.699
Relationships have to be sometimes built over time.

00:37:49.739 --> 00:37:58.139
I am a just serial over-promiser or I promise things too soon.

00:37:58.139 --> 00:38:02.459
And then I have to explain why they're not there when I said they were going to be there.

00:38:02.459 --> 00:38:07.659
Because for me, I think I just, I'm a little bit of an optimist,

00:38:07.659 --> 00:38:09.020
that will be done in three months.

00:38:09.580 --> 00:38:14.139
And five months later, the project's still not done.

00:38:14.139 --> 00:38:21.020
So just, yeah, being more pragmatic about things,

00:38:21.020 --> 00:38:25.659
being more patient, that's probably been the biggest

00:38:26.540 --> 00:38:31.100
personal thing that I've had to grow into over time.

00:38:34.300 --> 00:38:34.860
Thank you.

00:38:36.139 --> 00:38:41.100
Sundae, I see you had a question around pivoting between industries.

00:38:41.100 --> 00:38:42.300
Do you want to jump in here?

00:38:44.139 --> 00:38:44.639
Sure.

00:38:45.500 --> 00:38:49.260
Yeah, great talk so far, really good.

00:38:50.379 --> 00:38:53.340
And yeah, I was just thinking, in the past,

00:38:53.899 --> 00:38:57.820
I've kind of thought about it a couple of years ago,

00:38:57.820 --> 00:39:01.020
and I've been in health all my life.

00:39:01.020 --> 00:39:06.620
And I've always wondered, what is it like crossing over to finance?

00:39:07.419 --> 00:39:08.939
Is it more niche?

00:39:08.939 --> 00:39:10.139
Is there something special?

00:39:11.419 --> 00:39:12.379
What's it like?

00:39:12.379 --> 00:39:16.459
Or is it simply once I get to know the data and I see what data is,

00:39:16.459 --> 00:39:19.739
it's all the same, it's generic anyway, you learn.

00:39:19.739 --> 00:39:21.580
And have you had to work with people like that,

00:39:22.300 --> 00:39:25.659
people from health or some other industry?

00:39:25.659 --> 00:39:26.780
And how do they perform?

00:39:26.780 --> 00:39:27.500
How do they do?

00:39:28.219 --> 00:39:31.820
Yeah, so I want to flip, I'd almost ask you the same question.

00:39:31.820 --> 00:39:35.580
St. Louis is kind of a health care hub, or at least we like to think we are.

00:39:35.580 --> 00:39:42.060
We have a University of Washington here, which is a big medical school.

00:39:42.060 --> 00:39:46.219
And I've thought, all these people are right there, data science.

00:39:47.340 --> 00:39:49.419
The skill set is portable.

00:39:50.139 --> 00:39:57.340
Honestly, I would take anybody who has a problem solving mindset,

00:39:59.179 --> 00:40:02.379
familiarity with some of these open source tools.

00:40:03.179 --> 00:40:07.419
I wouldn't care if you knew anything about a financial model, I would want you on my team.

00:40:09.100 --> 00:40:11.179
That's the state of where we are today.

00:40:11.179 --> 00:40:17.820
That's kind of answering an early question too, probably better than how I tried before,

00:40:17.820 --> 00:40:25.739
about, yeah, there being a gap in skills in our industry.

00:40:27.739 --> 00:40:30.939
Yeah, because for finance, at least where I am,

00:40:32.300 --> 00:40:35.659
they're just, we just have to model.

00:40:35.659 --> 00:40:37.179
It's statistical models.

00:40:37.179 --> 00:40:44.139
So it's, you know, whether it's predicting prepayments of mortgages, right?

00:40:44.139 --> 00:40:47.580
If a customer is going to refinance on their mortgage or not,

00:40:47.580 --> 00:40:52.060
we need some statistical confidence that they are or they aren't,

00:40:52.060 --> 00:40:56.860
based on how interest rates have changed over the last six months, right?

00:40:56.860 --> 00:41:00.300
Because we have to make, you know, we have to keep the bank running.

00:41:00.300 --> 00:41:07.260
We can't, if everybody refinanced their mortgage tomorrow, these serious issues.

00:41:07.820 --> 00:41:18.620
So, yeah, models, yeah, data, exploring just data and being able to tell data stories.

00:41:19.739 --> 00:41:22.620
I do, I think those skill sets are totally portable.

00:41:24.060 --> 00:41:24.620
Awesome, thanks.

00:41:27.340 --> 00:41:34.459
Thinking about that example you just shared, like doing an analysis for the prepayment of mortgage.

00:41:35.340 --> 00:41:40.300
How do you go about that use case or like, how do you share that with business stakeholders?

00:41:40.300 --> 00:41:40.939
Trade theory.

00:41:40.939 --> 00:41:41.419
Yeah.

00:41:41.419 --> 00:41:41.979
No, I'm kidding.

00:41:43.100 --> 00:41:49.820
No, they are, there's, I mean, it's a model with like hundreds of nodes.

00:41:50.379 --> 00:41:52.620
It's a pretty sophisticated beast.

00:41:53.260 --> 00:41:58.620
Well, I guess I mean, like, how do you expose that model to others across the company?

00:41:59.500 --> 00:42:00.939
Or how do people interact with it?

00:42:01.020 --> 00:42:01.580
Oh, okay.

00:42:01.580 --> 00:42:06.060
So, yeah, we had that model is written in C++, it's got an API.

00:42:06.939 --> 00:42:12.219
So, we have several models that kind of, for our like models that we use,

00:42:14.219 --> 00:42:21.419
kind of what I would say in production, or they are used every day or every month,

00:42:22.860 --> 00:42:27.100
and they kind of feed other downstream reporting or they feed databases.

00:42:27.100 --> 00:42:31.500
We usually try to use compiled languages for that work.

00:42:32.219 --> 00:42:35.659
It doesn't have to be, but that's just kind of the culture here.

00:42:36.699 --> 00:42:40.060
We'll write that in C-sharp or C++ normally.

00:42:40.060 --> 00:42:44.540
So, our prepayment and default models are written in C++.

00:42:45.100 --> 00:42:51.020
They feed a cash flow engine and evaluation engine that was originally written in R,

00:42:51.820 --> 00:42:53.659
but now is in C-sharp.

00:42:53.979 --> 00:42:58.219
And then though that data is written to a SQL database, right?

00:42:59.979 --> 00:43:03.419
Now, any reporting logic that we want to do or data analysis,

00:43:04.060 --> 00:43:08.860
we like to keep that flexible because that changes frequently, right?

00:43:08.860 --> 00:43:13.340
The models hopefully don't change very frequently, just the inputs to the models change

00:43:13.340 --> 00:43:15.340
or model assumptions can change.

00:43:15.340 --> 00:43:20.620
But the model logic themselves, just for governance purposes alone,

00:43:21.179 --> 00:43:25.179
should stay pretty, yeah, locked down.

00:43:26.219 --> 00:43:32.219
It's a whole circus to get internal governance teams to sign off on model changes.

00:43:32.219 --> 00:43:33.020
It sucks.

00:43:33.659 --> 00:43:39.820
But anyway, our reporting logic, data analytics logic, we want that in R,

00:43:39.820 --> 00:43:44.699
we want that in Python and other loose, more flexible things.

00:43:44.699 --> 00:43:47.260
And we manage that like reporting code.

00:43:47.419 --> 00:43:52.219
Like reporting code, we use GitHub, like enterprise GitHub to manage all that.

00:43:53.820 --> 00:43:54.320
Yeah.

00:43:55.179 --> 00:43:55.659
Cool.

00:43:55.659 --> 00:43:56.159
Thank you.

00:43:56.780 --> 00:43:58.860
Jacob, I see you just asked something in the chat.

00:43:58.860 --> 00:43:59.739
Want to jump in here?

00:44:02.379 --> 00:44:02.620
Yeah.

00:44:02.620 --> 00:44:03.500
Hey, Michael.

00:44:03.500 --> 00:44:08.860
I'm just wondering if you guys at Wells Fargo share any of your data science or quant use

00:44:08.860 --> 00:44:09.899
cases online.

00:44:09.899 --> 00:44:15.340
Do you have any sort of repository where you share projects that have gone over well with

00:44:15.340 --> 00:44:15.840
the company?

00:44:16.800 --> 00:44:20.639
So I have not personally, and I don't know.

00:44:20.639 --> 00:44:25.280
I would say my just instinct is that we don't.

00:44:27.679 --> 00:44:28.959
I wish the answer was different.

00:44:30.479 --> 00:44:30.719
Yeah.

00:44:30.719 --> 00:44:31.040
Okay.

00:44:31.040 --> 00:44:31.540
Thanks.

00:44:33.439 --> 00:44:36.879
I know you just mentioned GitHub and Rick had a question earlier.

00:44:36.879 --> 00:44:40.479
I know he had to leave for a meeting, but I'll ask it for the recording.

00:44:41.520 --> 00:44:44.159
But to what degree does your team use GitHub?

00:44:44.159 --> 00:44:50.239
And Rick said, in my experience, data science folks tend to be intimidated by the complexity

00:44:50.239 --> 00:44:54.560
of GitHub to the point where some consider it a specialty unto itself.

00:44:55.120 --> 00:44:56.560
Yeah, I do too.

00:44:56.560 --> 00:44:58.479
I consider it its own skill.

00:45:00.320 --> 00:45:04.479
And it was hard for me to learn.

00:45:04.479 --> 00:45:07.919
It was not native really.

00:45:07.919 --> 00:45:09.679
It didn't click right away.

00:45:09.679 --> 00:45:12.479
It took a lot of time of brute force learning.

00:45:12.479 --> 00:45:14.159
And so that's what I tell my team.

00:45:14.159 --> 00:45:17.040
I'm like, this is going to be tough.

00:45:17.040 --> 00:45:18.080
I know that it's tough.

00:45:19.600 --> 00:45:22.800
Force, force it, force it, keep forcing it.

00:45:22.800 --> 00:45:23.840
We can do it wrong.

00:45:24.560 --> 00:45:25.760
Doesn't matter.

00:45:25.760 --> 00:45:31.280
But let's keep practicing and get so that we, and I would say we've done that for about

00:45:31.280 --> 00:45:34.560
six months now and the team now loves it.

00:45:34.560 --> 00:45:36.080
It is working fantastic.

00:45:37.120 --> 00:45:40.879
So I totally agree that the upfront cost, the learning, it's intimidating.

00:45:40.879 --> 00:45:41.520
It's difficult.

00:45:43.040 --> 00:45:49.919
But I mean, man, once, now that we have it and we're branching off work and borrowing

00:45:49.919 --> 00:45:54.560
and re-merging and it's so slick.

00:45:56.080 --> 00:46:00.879
Yeah, I just, it's like working out.

00:46:00.879 --> 00:46:03.600
You just got to sometimes do it even when it's not fun.

00:46:04.560 --> 00:46:10.560
Let me just double check that there weren't some questions that I missed earlier.

00:46:10.560 --> 00:46:15.760
There was a specific question around Shiny and it maybe was a little bit more detailed,

00:46:15.760 --> 00:46:17.360
but so maybe I'll ask first.

00:46:17.360 --> 00:46:18.800
Do you use Shiny?

00:46:18.800 --> 00:46:20.560
I have in the past.

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:30.479
I've used Shiny in the past and right now the powers above me, probably the executive

00:46:30.959 --> 00:46:35.600
level, hear about Power BI all the time, right?

00:46:35.600 --> 00:46:37.439
And think that that's good.

00:46:37.439 --> 00:46:38.479
The same thing.

00:46:41.040 --> 00:46:48.639
It's hard for me to communicate upward or has been so far to say that they're not the

00:46:48.639 --> 00:46:56.719
same thing, that I'm a lot, I'm able to more dynamically put models into Shiny than I can

00:46:56.719 --> 00:46:58.239
into Power BI, right?

00:46:59.199 --> 00:47:04.479
Where I can look at different models and different versions of models and dynamically produce

00:47:04.479 --> 00:47:09.360
results that have kind of sophisticated calculations and things like that.

00:47:10.639 --> 00:47:13.760
So that's something that I'm continuing to advocate for.

00:47:15.840 --> 00:47:22.719
Luckily, I've had some economists that I work with in the company that love R and love Shiny.

00:47:22.800 --> 00:47:29.280
And so they, a long time ago, got like a Linux box and they host a bunch of Shiny reporting

00:47:29.280 --> 00:47:32.719
on there for their kind of economic research.

00:47:33.600 --> 00:47:36.239
I'll borrow that from them every once in a while.

00:47:36.239 --> 00:47:37.040
Some space there.

00:47:39.040 --> 00:47:44.560
I think it should be one of the resources that any kind of mature operation has.

00:47:45.120 --> 00:47:48.159
It's just, especially now that Python plugs right into it.

00:47:48.159 --> 00:47:48.639
It's great.

00:47:50.639 --> 00:47:51.120
Awesome.

00:47:51.120 --> 00:47:51.520
Thank you.

00:47:52.399 --> 00:47:57.760
Well, a question I always like to ask on Hangouts, and maybe one day I'm going to actually go

00:47:57.760 --> 00:48:00.479
and take all of these little clips and put them together.

00:48:01.199 --> 00:48:02.560
I really want to do that.

00:48:02.560 --> 00:48:08.479
But is there a piece of career advice that you've received over the course of your career

00:48:08.479 --> 00:48:13.439
or maybe a piece of career advice you give others that you'd like to share with us?

00:48:14.399 --> 00:48:16.239
Oh, man, I don't know.

00:48:16.639 --> 00:48:26.560
Um, I feel like my spiel earlier about trying to be collaborative because eventually technical

00:48:26.560 --> 00:48:28.399
skill doesn't scale anymore.

00:48:29.040 --> 00:48:35.760
I feel like that is kind of my really, that's my frame of thinking right now.

00:48:37.679 --> 00:48:43.199
And then I've received a lot of good advice and not, not always just even verbal.

00:48:43.199 --> 00:48:48.080
Sometimes it's just consistent support, um, coverage.

00:48:48.080 --> 00:48:56.080
I've had good bosses that have given me coverage to think about problems, um, not feel rushed

00:48:56.080 --> 00:48:57.360
to come to a conclusion.

00:48:58.080 --> 00:49:03.919
Um, and so I, I try to pass that forward, pass that on to my team.

00:49:04.560 --> 00:49:06.320
I don't want them to feel any pressure.

00:49:06.639 --> 00:49:14.479
So if people find themselves in kind of a manager role or even a VP role or a director

00:49:14.479 --> 00:49:20.719
or whatever, I would say the best thing that you can do is try to provide some shelter

00:49:20.719 --> 00:49:28.159
for your team to take their time to, to, to find a better solution.

00:49:28.159 --> 00:49:33.120
Maybe not just the first solution because I think it pays dividends in the end.

00:49:33.120 --> 00:49:38.879
So I don't, I don't know if that is a great response, but that's, that's what I have in

00:49:38.879 --> 00:49:39.679
my head.

00:49:39.679 --> 00:49:40.800
Oh, that's great.

00:49:40.800 --> 00:49:41.280
Thank you.

00:49:42.639 --> 00:49:50.159
I really like when you were describing, uh, earlier and in our hangout today about when

00:49:50.159 --> 00:49:54.959
you're trying to change the status quo, like building something in, in parallel.

00:49:55.600 --> 00:50:00.000
And I thought that's like, it's a really nice approach to that rather than saying like,

00:50:00.000 --> 00:50:02.000
Hey, we have to replace this right away.

00:50:02.800 --> 00:50:08.159
Um, and I was just wondering like, what's the, what's the next step there?

00:50:08.159 --> 00:50:12.239
So you build it in parallel and then you just tell somebody, Hey, this is a better way of

00:50:12.239 --> 00:50:12.879
doing it.

00:50:12.879 --> 00:50:15.439
Like check this out or what are the steps there?

00:50:15.439 --> 00:50:22.320
I think it depends on who you're, who's the customer, who's, who's going to use it, who's

00:50:22.320 --> 00:50:24.080
going to benefit from it.

00:50:24.080 --> 00:50:31.360
If it's somebody that built this legacy process over years and this is their baby, the best

00:50:31.360 --> 00:50:33.600
approach is not to go, Hey, this is way better.

00:50:34.639 --> 00:50:35.679
You have to use this.

00:50:35.679 --> 00:50:37.120
This is going to crush your thing.

00:50:37.919 --> 00:50:41.760
Um, no, for that, I have to bring them along.

00:50:42.479 --> 00:50:44.560
It's gotta be a little bit of inception, right?

00:50:45.360 --> 00:50:51.840
You gotta, you gotta teach them a little bit about it, kind of bring them to water.

00:50:51.840 --> 00:50:57.760
Um, that's, that's how I found to be most successful in that place.

00:50:58.639 --> 00:51:05.120
Um, I think if it is a boss or a manager and they're really more result oriented, then I

00:51:05.120 --> 00:51:07.199
think that's the language that you have to speak.

00:51:07.199 --> 00:51:13.040
Um, listen, you have a team of people that are dedicated to building this one report

00:51:13.040 --> 00:51:19.199
because it's so complicated and it, you know, if someone gets sick, you have to have coverage

00:51:19.199 --> 00:51:20.000
on it.

00:51:20.000 --> 00:51:22.959
Well, this thing that I built, it runs automatically.

00:51:22.959 --> 00:51:28.320
It has three inputs, you know, and it, it links to this, this, and this, and it's all

00:51:28.320 --> 00:51:32.080
tracked and version controlled and blah, blah, blah.

00:51:32.080 --> 00:51:36.639
You can, you can spin that story pretty easily to the people out there.

00:51:36.639 --> 00:51:41.360
And they've usually after the first 30 seconds, they've already decided, right?

00:51:41.360 --> 00:51:46.320
And so their question is going to say, okay, how do you sunset the old thing and how do

00:51:46.320 --> 00:51:47.439
you replace the new thing?

00:51:48.000 --> 00:51:54.000
Got to communicate to anybody that touches this thing that, um, hey, it's going away.

00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:57.840
It's going away in a quarter and here's the new thing.

00:51:57.840 --> 00:51:59.679
You can find it here, right?

00:52:00.479 --> 00:52:04.159
Um, yeah, that's, that's how we've, we've done.

00:52:07.360 --> 00:52:07.760
Thank you.

00:52:08.879 --> 00:52:13.919
Um, I also wanted to dig a little bit deeper into the coaching that you brought up in the

00:52:13.919 --> 00:52:14.719
beginning too.

00:52:14.719 --> 00:52:19.040
So you said it gets a little bit newer to be in this coaching role.

00:52:19.040 --> 00:52:26.320
So are there some lessons learned so far in that coaching role or maybe even books that

00:52:26.320 --> 00:52:29.360
you'd recommend for some of us who are new to that?

00:52:29.919 --> 00:52:31.840
Oh, no, no.

00:52:31.840 --> 00:52:40.639
Unfortunately, I think all my coaching, uh, for better or for worse, for sure, uh, is

00:52:40.639 --> 00:52:43.439
from, you know, playing sports.

00:52:43.439 --> 00:52:47.760
And then also I used to do like improv, uh, a lot.

00:52:47.760 --> 00:52:53.520
And so like that collaboration and teamwork and trying to, so, um, I feel like that's

00:52:53.520 --> 00:52:55.919
what I try to pull from is that background.

00:52:56.479 --> 00:53:00.479
Um, I probably should read more about managing people.

00:53:01.040 --> 00:53:03.600
Um, so guilty.

00:53:04.320 --> 00:53:12.159
Um, however, lessons, I think I, I have learned to let go a little bit.

00:53:12.159 --> 00:53:19.360
I think a lot of people that come from a quantitative data science role, uh, they've

00:53:19.360 --> 00:53:26.719
spent so many times, so much time solving problems, thinking through how best to do

00:53:26.719 --> 00:53:28.800
things, how to organize things.

00:53:28.800 --> 00:53:33.280
I think we can be control freaks sometimes, and I am very guilty of that.

00:53:33.280 --> 00:53:38.239
And so learning to let go and learning to let other people make that call and really

00:53:38.239 --> 00:53:40.399
just trusting that it's good.

00:53:41.120 --> 00:53:47.040
And, and taking the result and moving on, you know, um, take the win and move on.

00:53:47.600 --> 00:53:49.679
Don't be a stickler on, on things.

00:53:49.679 --> 00:53:52.159
Don't burn a bridge for something that's worthless.

00:53:52.719 --> 00:53:54.320
You know, it's just a preference.

00:53:55.199 --> 00:54:01.040
Um, yeah, that's, that's something that, uh, has had to be learned.

00:54:03.360 --> 00:54:07.760
Would you, would you recommend improv to us for some data storytelling?

00:54:07.760 --> 00:54:11.439
Uh, I would recommend improv to anyone.

00:54:11.439 --> 00:54:17.360
Um, it's been a long time since I've done that, but man, it just forcing yourself to

00:54:17.360 --> 00:54:22.959
be a little bit more open, a little more accepting, um, listening, a lot of listening.

00:54:24.000 --> 00:54:24.500
Yeah.

00:54:25.919 --> 00:54:27.120
How did you get into that?

00:54:28.159 --> 00:54:33.520
Oh, I had a friend in high school that probably, uh, said it was fun.

00:54:33.520 --> 00:54:37.280
And so I did, and then I did it through college and through my twenties.

00:54:37.840 --> 00:54:38.340
Yeah.

00:54:40.560 --> 00:54:45.280
So thinking about, I guess, as we get to the end of the hangout here, thinking about

00:54:45.280 --> 00:54:50.719
like the next year ahead for your team, is there something that you're really excited

00:54:50.719 --> 00:54:51.219
about?

00:54:51.840 --> 00:54:55.360
Oh man, I'm very excited, uh, about this year.

